      <body>
        <div>
            <pb facs="#TL-0444.jpg" n="part3_p052.jpg" xml:id="img_0052" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/part3_p052.jpg"/>
            
            <p facs="#facs_52_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>dʼun autre
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>dʼavoir eu que je
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>139.
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>Now when you have these three concepts of the individual, it would be good if you
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_2_tl_5" n="N005"/>always keep them asunder and don’t fall into the many troops and confusions which will immediately
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_2_tl_6" n="N006"/>follow if you confuse them, if you don’t keep them asunder.
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_2_tl_7" n="N007"/>I come now to another concept, the concept of person, or personality. The person
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_2_tl_8" n="N008"/>arises on the basis of the individual human being. There are also legal persons, such as corporations,
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_2_tl_9" n="N009"/>but we can leave them out for our present tonsidérations and concentrate on person as something
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_2_tl_10" n="N010"/>I will say immediately what—which Leises on the basis of individual human existence. What is that?
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_52_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>When we Caussed morality as one of the functions of man's spiritual life—in the
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/>beginning of this section of our lectures—we said morality is the totally of those
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>acts in which an individual person setz itself, or establishes itself, as an individual person. This was
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>the general definition of morality, in order to avoid the elstoried form of morality that it is obedience
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>to a set of laws whereby one would ask "Why?" "Where do the laws come from?" "Why do I have
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/>to be obedient to them?" If, however, we say that the principle of morality is the principle of the
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_52_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_1" n="N001"/>self-establishment of the persons as persona, then the situation is different; then it isn’t estrenged
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_2" n="N002"/>law; then it is ME OURSELVES who are centrally involved in the acts of morality.
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_3" n="N003"/>Persona— person : where does it come from? The word has a long history, and it is
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_4" n="N004"/>pitfalls in the philosophy of religion
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_5" n="N005"/>very important to know it in order especially to avoid
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_6" n="N006"/>and calling God "a Person"—which some people still do, in popular nonsense. But if we are clear
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_7" n="N007"/>what persona means, then we would avoid such a thing.
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_8" n="N008"/>cʼest en lʼautre
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_9" n="N009"/>dʼauteur ses
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_10" n="N010"/>Monsieur Mounard et le précaire
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_11" n="N011"/>Monsieur M r de
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_12" n="N012"/>dʼune manière
               <lb facs="#facs_52_tr_1_tl_13" n="N013"/>dʼadresse
            </p>
            
